						I think the trade skills could be made to be more profitable.  I do like the idea of implementing them in quest, yet the high price to build a decent skill level in a skill is just way too much.  There are some skills out there that just seem too silly.  Pottery?  Whats that one all about?  Not only should the skills be more profitable, but should have some value quest or not.  
						
						</font>
					  </td>
                    </tr>
					 
					
				    <tr>
                      <td width="6%" valign="top" align="center" bgcolor="bfbf80" background=""><font face="arial" color="4a0000" size="3"><b>3.</b></font></td>
                      <td width="94%" valign="top" bgcolor="CDCD9C"><font face="arial" size="2"><b>Response from:
                        Balaern</b>
                        </font><font face="arial" size="1"> - Monday, Jun 19, 2000 at 4:54 PM</font><font face="arial" size="2"><br>
						
						
						Adding to the trade skills to make them more versatile, such as making the ability to create magical and stat increasing armor, would be a good idea. Also make them interelated. Such that one skill could use some items from another skill (somewhat like how a blacksmith can make a tinker's toolbox), tailors could create some material parts used in making armor.... perhaps broaden the range of items that can be created as well... also, as with current fletching trade skill, all trade skills should be made profitable... having NEW quests that would involve trade skills seems to be a good idea too, but have them spread out over levels... so that there would be trade quests for low, mid, and high level items... of which they could span only a small area and also large areas (perhaps according to the level range for the quest)... some new trade skills could also be a good idea... like "forage" type ones... like mining for ore or gems... different types of ore could be mined in different mines or caves around norrath... blacksmiths could use the different types of ore to make armor made from different materials... perhaps even add gems to the armor to create an stat modifying armor... (of course the materials would have to be enchanted first)...
						
						</font>
					  </td>
                    </tr>
					 
					
